title: Georgia Southern Cycling Road Race Weekend
MGC 07.02 | Downtown Gaineville Grand Prix
description:
Round two of the MAXXIS Georgia Cup is in Gainesville, known as the Chicken City, and this race is guaranteed to be a barn burner!  Everyone has found their legs for spring and there is no holding back at this point.  Those who competed in Albany already have points on the board and those who didn\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\'t can\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\'t afford to miss the break.  Gainesville presents a truly well-rounded event with each of the courses favoring a different style of rider.

The Thurmond Tanner Parkway Time Trial will bring the true competitors to the foray.  Not just a prologue, this is an out and back course that riders can put their head down and really bury themselves.

The Downtown Gainesville Gran Prix is one of the fastest courses in the southeast.  The slight bends through the downtown square that cause the peleton to snake through the long straightaways produce unbelievable speeds.  The Yellow Jersey wearer will have to fight to maintain the lead, but everyone else will be looking to take to the front and determine their own fate.

Sunday\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\'s Road Race will be the proving grounds for those who can get over the hills, and will identify the contenders for the upcoming races in Dahlonega, Rome, and Augusta.  The course runs clockwise around a rock quarry, hopping over some railroad tracks and then careening down through the country before taking a difficult right just before a kilometer-plus climb to the top of the hill.  Look for the climbers to be giving \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"the look\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" to last night\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\'s winners just before they scamper away for the KOM.
course:
Thurmond Tanner Time Trial.  The Thurmond Tanner Time Trial is a 10k out and back course with some slightly undulating hills, but comparatively flat and should see some fast times turned.  A huge effort here could carry the winner all the way to Sunday in the Yellow Jersey.

Downtown Gainesville Grand Prix. This is one of the fastest Criteriums in the series.  The course is flat and with two short sides, open corners, and two long straights that run the length of the downtown, the action stays hot all night.  Passing by the downtown square on both sides of the course as the peleton speeds around the downtown keeps everyone excited and active until the final bell.  Riders will be fighting to stay at the front to make sure no one gets away and begins to gain time on the field.  Two strategies will certainly be simultaneously employed as riders looking to steal a victory or make a jump on the leaderboard will be attacking all night and pushing the limits through the corners while teams trying to maintain their riders position on GC will be keeping a tight leash on the field. 

Hall County Road Race.  With Saturday\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\'s winners having mastered the Time Trial and the Criterium, this route is one for the power-climbers.  With the GC far from decided and final placings still up for grabs, this route will definitely find the KOM contenders showing their cards early in the year.  The course seems relatively unassuming at first, as it winds its way down towards the backside of the course, but the tension will grow as it becomes vital to move to the front before hitting the Mabery Wall, 1.5k at 9% grade to the KOM, then a right turn over the railroad tracks, another 700m climb to the second KOM at the finish, and one last 500m bump before shooting back down the hill to do it all over again.  Teams can try as they may, but this course is going to make it virtually impossible to maintain the breaks, so the best bet will be to cover them if you can.
